04989nmm a2200601Ia 9780520390560DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203905607 a10.1525/97805203905602doi  a(DE-B1597)649730  a(OCoLC)1374540612  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN1995.9.A6955bM33 2023 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.430911/30905223/eng/202208161 aStenport, Anna Westerstahl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Arctic Cinemas :bMedia Sovereignty and the Climate Crisis /cAnna Westerstahl Stenport. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Twenty-First-Century Arctic Cinemas and Global Media Studies, Media Sovereignty, the Anthropocene, and Interventionist Historiography -- t2 New Arctic Explorers and Twenty-First-Century Ice Imaginaries: From Metrical Documentary to IMAX Spectacle -- t3 Isuma and Indigenous Media Sovereignty -- t4 The Arnait Collective, Feminist Practice, and Inuit Self-Determination -- t5 Sámi Media Sovereignty and Interventionist Historiography: Environmental, Experimental, and Archival Politics -- t6 Sámi Feminist First-Person Documentary and Women’s Activism -- t7 Global Greenland and Postcolonial Cinema -- t8 Greenlandic Reconciliation Cinema, Self-Determination, and Interventionist Historiography -- t9 Russia’s Contemporary Arctic Cinema as Geopolitics -- t10 From the Cold War to the Climate Crisis: The Russian North and Utopian Svalbard -- t11 Looking Ahead: Global Arctic Cinemas in the Twenty-First Century -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor centuries, the Arctic was visualized as an unchanging, stable, and rigidly alien landscape, existing outside twenty-first-century globalization. It is now impossible to ignore the ways the climate crisis, expanding resource extraction, and Indigenous political mobilization in the circumpolar North are constituent parts of the global present. New Arctic Cinemas presents an original, comparative, and interventionist historiography of film and media in twenty-first-century Scandinavia, Greenland, Russia, Canada, and the United States to situate Arctic media in the place it rightfully deserves to occupy: as central to global environmental concerns and Indigenous media sovereignty and self-determination movements. The works of contemporary Arctic filmmakers, from Zacharias Kunuk and Alethea Arnaquq-Baril to Amanda Kernell and Inuk Silis Høegh, reach worldwide audiences. In examining the reach and influence of these artists and their work, Scott MacKenzie and Anna Westerstahl Stenport reveal a global media system of intertwined production contexts, circulation opportunities, and imaginaries—all centering the Arctic North.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion pictureszArctic regionsy21st century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2023z9783111318103oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2023 Englishz978311131903208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520390560?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520390560